          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              Maybe I'm wrong but this is one of those issues I don't worry all that much about. There are a lot of things in need of regulation and protection and I would certainly support this bill but I feel this is one of those few times when &quot;free market capitalism&quot; will actually work well to protect the consumer. <br /><br />If you start enforcing hard data caps on me or choking my video streaming I'm going to switch ISPs and I really believe that smaller ISPs (or not so small ones) will jump at the chance to steal a huge section of someone's customer base by offering &quot;no caps&quot; or guaranteeing &quot;no throttling&quot;. <br /><br />Of course I expected something similar to happen with the ridiculous texting charges too and it is but it took a hell of a lot longer than I thought it would. <br /><br />On second thought, yeah lets pass some laws.<br /><br />Edit: So apparently this is basically just reddit now eh? Someone posts a story and if someone has an opinion you don't like you just destroy them with downvotes. You know I wasn't rude, insulting, or in any other way inappropriate. I expressed a line of thought that you may not agree with (or may think is failing to take other factors into consideration) and that used to be fine on Ars, people would respond and you'd talk about it, I guess that isn't how we're going to do things any more. Maybe I should just start thinking of witty one liners and try to get them in early enough to gather some yummy upvotes.<br /><br />My thanks to those who replied to me pointing out some of the flaws in my line of thought and educating me on other situations.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
