        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=25677781#p25677781" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">SiberX</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">I worry about the wording of the bill being so video distribution focused; the points and provisions made are sensible, but tailoring the bill to video traffic specifically simply opens the door for the same kind of behaviour on a different kind of traffic down the road (audio, streamed web applications, etc...) - why not just make the bill target generic content?</div><br />Because they're not arguing for true net neutrality.  Legal video as defined by the RIAA/MPAA would be covered, but if they wanted to throttle your torrent traffic, even on only suspicion you might be pirating videos, they could and not break the law. It also doesn't cover other legitimate uses for large data transfers either.<br /><br />They need to treat the entire internet as a fat dumb pipe, open up the last mile to real competition, and be done with it.  There is too much of a conflict of interest in media holding companies also being ISPs.

              

              
              
            </div>
