        <tr>
          <td class="post-content">
            <div class="post-content-inner">
              
              This bill sounds like a great idea, but it doesn't have a chance of passing.  Republicans are vehemently opposed to anything approaching Net Neutrality, and this is squarely in that vein.  They believe that, if you want to compete, you should provide a better product that everyone wants or build your own network.  The problem with that is how the government has, essentially, given cable companies practical monopolies in their various areas for decades now.  Only now are real options for networks popping up, and even those aren't terribly good in some areas.  To build your own network would not only be prohibitively expensive, but the current providers already have a leg up that would allow them to out-compete any start-ups.  That's why Verizon FIOS, municipal fiber, and city-wide WiFi are so important.  Unfortunately, Verizon quit expanding FIOS and the other two are growing only slowly.

              

              
              
            </div>
          </td>
        </tr>
        
    </table>
    
